etymologies: late Middle English. From pannier + man

definitions: A man in charge of a pannier or panniers; especially a hawker of fish, etc., who transports his goods to market in a pannier or panniers. Now rare (chiefly English regional in later use).
A paid officer at the Inns of Court, who brought provisions from market and (in later times at least) had duties relating to the serving of meals. Compare "pannier".

notes.text: This office was abolished at the Inner Temple in 1900.
